Task 1

In this task, I tried to find out if the “bookmakers” are good at setting their odds for different games. To understand this, the data given(match and odd) first transformed into “data table” form, which is a fast data manipulation tool of R. After that, some variables have been manipulated or created into a more usable form, such as dates and total goal values. Then, match and odd data is merged to create a one data table for practicality. After that, implied probability values are calculated using the formula given in the question sheet. Lastly, first and last set odds are found. While doing these, the games with over-under bet types and with handicap greater than 2.5 are considered.

MatchDataPath='/Users/furkancetinkaya/Desktop/ie582/582/df9b1196-e3cf-4cc7-9159-f236fe738215_matches.rds'
OddDataPath='/Users/furkancetinkaya/Desktop/ie582/582/df9b1196-e3cf-4cc7-9159-f236fe738215_odd_details.rds'
MatchData<-readRDS(MatchDataPath)
OddData<-readRDS(OddDataPath)
MatchData<-as.data.table(MatchData)
OddData<-as.data.table(OddData)
MatchData$date<-as.data.table(as.Date(anytime(MatchData[,date])))
OddData$date<-as.data.table(as.Date(anytime(OddData[,date])))           ### reading data as data.table
DT1a<-as.data.table(OddData[betType=="ou"&totalhandicap==2.5])         ## selecting the needed features
DT1a$year<-year(as.Date(DT1a$date, "%Y-%m-%d"))                       ##taking the year out of date
bin <- seq(from=0, to=1,by=0.05)                                      ##creating bins
ranges <-as.data.table(paste(head(bin,-1), bin[-1], sep=" - "))          ##creating bin ranges
DT1a=DT1a[complete.cases(DT1a)]                                           
MatchData <- separate(MatchData, col=score, into=c("homescore","awayscore"),sep=":")          ##seperates the home-away scores
MatchData$TotalGoal<-as.numeric(MatchData[,homescore])+as.numeric(MatchData[,awayscore])      ##calculates total score
DT1a=DT1a[order(date)]                                                           ##ordering by date
DT1a[,noofodds:=seq_len(.N), by = c("bookmaker","matchId","oddtype") ]           ##creates a column that stores ordered odd numbers
DT1a=merge(DT1a, MatchData[,c("matchId","TotalGoal")], by="matchId")             ##merging match and odd data
implied_prob_table<-aggregate(DT1a$odd, by=list(DT1a$matchId, DT1a$bookmaker, DT1a$date, DT1a$noofodds), FUN=function(x)(prod(x)/(sum(x))))   ##first step of implied probability calculation
colnames(implied_prob_table)<-c("matchId", "bookmaker", "date", "noofodds","implied_prob")
DT1a=merge(DT1a,implied_prob_table[,c("matchId","bookmaker","date","noofodds","implied_prob")],by=c("matchId","bookmaker","date","noofodds"))
DT1a$implied_prob=DT1a$implied_prob/DT1a$odd              ##implied probability calculation
DT1a[,odd_cut:=cut(implied_prob,bin)]                     ##cutting implied probabilities in terms of bins
DT1a[,maxnoofodds:=max(noofodds),by=.(matchId,bookmaker)]         ##deciding the last given odd.

Part A

After creating the data tables I need, I plotted the graphs that show the relation between implied average probability given from bookmakers and match scores. If the dots on the graphs are close to x=y line, that means that the bookmaker used for this graph is good at determining their odds.

ranges <-as.data.table(paste(head(bin,-1), bin[-1], sep=" - ")) 
ranges$average_prob<-data.table(tapply(DT1a[oddtype=="over"&bookmaker=="Pinnacle"&noofodds==1]$implied_prob, cut(DT1a[oddtype=="over"&bookmaker=="Pinnacle"&noofodds==1]$implied_prob, seq(0, 1, by=0.05)), mean))            ##finds avarage implied probs
ranges$total_game<-data.table(tapply(DT1a[oddtype=="over"&bookmaker=="Pinnacle"&noofodds==1]$matchId, cut(DT1a[oddtype=="over"&bookmaker=="Pinnacle"&noofodds==1]$implied_prob, seq(0, 1, by=0.05)), length))   ##total game in a bin
ranges$over_games<-data.table(tapply(DT1a[TotalGoal > totalhandicap&bookmaker=="Pinnacle"&noofodds==1&oddtype=="over"]$matchId, cut(DT1a[TotalGoal > totalhandicap&bookmaker=="Pinnacle"&noofodds==1&oddtype=="over"]$implied_prob, seq(0, 1, by=0.05)), length))    ##over games in a bin
ranges$fraction<-ranges$over_games/ranges$total_game         ## fraction of games ended over
ranges=ranges[complete.cases(ranges)]
ggplot(ranges,aes(x=average_prob,y=fraction) )+ theme_bw() + geom_point()+ geom_abline(slope = 1, intercept = 0)+ ylim(0, 1) +labs(title="Pinnacle, over & initial odds",x="Probabilistic Over",y="Empirical Over")

ranges <-as.data.table(paste(head(bin,-1), bin[-1], sep=" - "))

ranges$total_game<-data.table(tapply(DT1a[oddtype=="over"&bookmaker=="Pinnacle"&noofodds==maxnoofodds]$matchId, cut(DT1a[oddtype=="over"&bookmaker=="Pinnacle"&noofodds==maxnoofodds]$implied_prob, seq(0, 1, by=0.05)), length))   ##total game in a bin
ranges$over_games<-data.table(tapply(DT1a[TotalGoal > totalhandicap&bookmaker=="Pinnacle"&noofodds==maxnoofodds&oddtype=="over"]$matchId, cut(DT1a[TotalGoal > totalhandicap&bookmaker=="Pinnacle"&noofodds==maxnoofodds&oddtype=="over"]$implied_prob, seq(0, 1, by=0.05)), length))    ##over games in a bin
ranges$fraction<-ranges$over_games/ranges$total_game         ## fraction of games ended over

For the rest of the graphs, the code is the same, I only added graphs.

From the graphs, I can conclude that several bookmakers are good at determining their odds in terms of probabilities. In every graph, whether first or last, the points are around the x=y line. I was expecting the last odds to perform better, however, I did not notice any difference. To be more precise, we have to check the accuracy values. However, both initial and final odds seem to perform decent.

Part B

For this part, we want to see if the bookmakers are good at setting their odds during the years. Again, empirical and probabilistic values for over probabilities are found. Then, several plots which show a different portion of bin gaps was drawn. Every plot shows probabilistic and empirical lines with seperate lines in the graph.

# BOOKMAKER CHOICE : "Pinnacle"
DT1a[,IsOver:=0]
DT1a[TotalGoal>2,IsOver:=1]   ## merges match and odd data
DT1b<-DT1a[bookmaker=="Pinnacle"&noofodds==1&oddtype=="over"]       ##selecting necessary variables
summary=DT1b[,list(empiricalover=sum(IsOver)/length(unique(matchId)),probabilisticover=mean(implied_prob)),
              by=list(year,odd_cut)]
summary=summary[order(year)]      ##time order

ggplot(summary[odd_cut=="(0.35,0.4]"], aes(year)) + geom_line(aes(y = probabilisticover, colour = "probabilisticover")) + geom_line(aes(y = empiricalover, colour = "empiricalover"))+labs(title="Pinnacle, yearly probabilities between bins: 0.35-0.4",x="year",y="probabilities")

ggplot(summary[odd_cut=="(0.4,0.45]"], aes(year)) + geom_line(aes(y = probabilisticover, colour = "probabilisticover")) + geom_line(aes(y = empiricalover, colour = "empiricalover"))+labs(title="Pinnacle, yearly probabilities between bins: 0.4-0.45",x="year",y="probabilities")

ggplot(summary[odd_cut=="(0.45,0.5]"], aes(year)) + geom_line(aes(y = probabilisticover, colour = "probabilisticover")) + geom_line(aes(y = empiricalover, colour = "empiricalover"))+labs(title="Pinnacle, yearly probabilities between bins: 0.45-0.5",x="year",y="probabilities")

ggplot(summary[odd_cut=="(0.5,0.55]"], aes(year)) + geom_line(aes(y = probabilisticover, colour = "probabilisticover")) + geom_line(aes(y = empiricalover, colour = "empiricalover"))+labs(title="Pinnacle, yearly probabilities between bins: 0.5-0.55",x="year",y="probabilities")

ggplot(summary[odd_cut=="(0.55,0.6]"], aes(year)) + geom_line(aes(y = probabilisticover, colour = "probabilisticover")) + geom_line(aes(y = empiricalover, colour = "empiricalover"))+labs(title="Pinnacle, yearly probabilities between bins: 0.55-0.6",x="year",y="probabilities")

ggplot(summary[odd_cut=="(0.6,0.65]"], aes(year)) + geom_line(aes(y = probabilisticover, colour = "probabilisticover")) + geom_line(aes(y = empiricalover, colour = "empiricalover"))+labs(title="Pinnacle, yearly probabilities between bins: 0.6-0.65",x="year",y="probabilities")

ggplot(summary[odd_cut=="(0.65,0.7]"], aes(year)) + geom_line(aes(y = probabilisticover, colour = "probabilisticover")) + geom_line(aes(y = empiricalover, colour = "empiricalover"))+labs(title="Pinnacle, yearly probabilities between bins: 0.65-0.7",x="year",y="probabilities")

As it can be seen from the graphs, probabilistic over rates are close to empirical rates. Especially in the bins “0.35-4” and “0.5-0.55”. However, some graphs show large deviations. That shows that, probabilistic over rates are not performing good to determine sudden changes. This may be happening because of human nature of the Football game. Some results may not be foreseen beforehand.

In this part, I tried to illustrate, for a single match, the odd changes made by the bookmaker. While I am doing this, I used the games which has a lot of odd changes. Then I tried to find some cases, such as home win with 4 more goals. Then I plotted the graphs, in which home, away and draw odds can be seen. With this way, increasing and decreasing odds can be easily observed, with their relative movements. I chose “10Bet” as the bookmaker and 1x2 bets as oddtype.

In “2LC3nF2G” case, it can be seen that bookmaker responded succesfully to the changes. Because, the odd for draw and away-win decreases, while the home-win increases.

In “6ZS0SgBp” case, the bookmaker increases the odd of away-win, which is a well-done move, since the away team lost 4-0.

In “8pYQYeYG” case, the bookmaker increases the home-win odd. Then, home team lost 1-4, which shows it is a good prediction.
